Parameter-Efficient Fine-tuning (PEFT) is a technique used in Natural Language Processing (NLP) to improve the performance of machine learning models. The idea behind PEFT is to fine-tune a pre-trained model on a small subset of the training dataset, with smaller models and a much lower resource requirement.
PEFT works by training the model on a small subset of the training dataset, instead of the entire dataset. This approach helps reduce the computational time and cost required to train the model. The small subset of the training dataset is a fixed-length input with a minimum and maximum length limit. The model is trained on this subset of the dataset and then evaluated on the full dataset. The use of PEFT can lead to significant improvements in the performance of machine learning models, particularly in low-resource scenarios where data is scarce.

A binary tree is a recursive data structure. It makes use of a binary search tree(BST)d, which is often an organised heap or tree structure. Binary trees are ordered mechanism of storage where every node can have instructions for exactly two children, except for a root node where there will be just a single reference to a tree to define the path to a certain key. Usually, a binary tree is an organised nested inheritance containing only two elements, a root and a leaf. They typically store data in a tree form. For instance, a dictionary is a binary tree having the keys as words, while the values are the meanings of the words. Each node of the binary tree holds a pointer to either a left node and a parent node or a right node and a parent node. Typically, a binary tree has two pointers for each node, however, a ternary search tree-which is a kind of binary search tree - has three pointers for every node. The smallest will be a reference to the left child node, and the largest is a pointer to the right child node. Typically, the middle location, which is the parent pointer pointer, is the largest.
